    <p>EVAN ELLIS: I think it would very quickly become a violent criminal mess. It would become a - basically a free-for-all.</p>
    <p>OTIS: The military's top brass has so far remained loyal to Maduro. Gaudio has offered amnesty to those who switch sides. But many officers may still fear prosecution for corruption, human rights abuses and other crimes should the opposition take power. In addition, Smilde says, many remain committed socialists and resent the calls for a coup, especially those coming out of Washington.</p>
    <p>SMILDE: You know, one of the things that keeps the military together is ideology, the anti-imperialists revolution that they're defending. And so I think the United States pressuring in that direction is probably not the most productive.</p>
    <p>OTIS: Venezuela's Defense Ministry did not reply to requests for comment. For NPR News, I'm John Otis.</p>
